[Event "Hoogovens Group A"]
[Site "Wijk aan Zee NED"]
[Date "1999.01.20"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Garry Kasparov"]
[Black "Veselin Topalov"]
[Result "1-0"]
[EventDate "1999.01.16"]
[ECO "B07"]
[WhiteElo "2812"]
[BlackElo "2700"]
[PlyCount "87"]
[Link "https://www.chess.com/blog/SamCopeland/the-greatest-chess-game-of-all-time-explained-kasparov-vs-topalov-1999"]

1. e4 {Kasparov has won many brilliant attacking games with both 1.e4 and 1.d4. Here he pursues an open game.} 1... d6 $5 {Kasparov is probably THE greatest opening theoretician of all time so it makes sense to avoid main lines against him. Topalov selects the less common Pirc Defense, but now he runs the risk of getting in trouble not because he is outprepared, but because the opening may be slightly dubious at the highest level.} 2. d4 {It is of course correct to establish the "perfect pawn center" against almost any hypermodern opening.} 2... Nf6 {Topalov attacks the e4-pawn.} 3. Nc3 {Kasparov develops and defends e4.} 3... g6 {Topalov commits to the true "Pirc" defense with a kingside fianchetto.} 4. Be3 {As is his way, Kasparov selects an aggressive setup, developing the bishop to pursue a quick queen and bishop battery and castle queenside.} 4... Bg7 {completing the fianchetto.} 5. Qd2 {This move already prepares queenside castling and Bh6.} 5... c6 $5 {An intriguing and flexible move! Rather than castling, Topalov adopts a very flexible expansion on the queenside.} (5... Ng4 $6 {Exchanging the dark-square bishop would be a huge strategic achievement, but Topalov would only overextend if he tried this move.} 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 $16 {The dark-square bishop survives, and Black's advanced kingside pawns may easily become targets.}) (5... O-O {Naturally Topalov avoids castling into the attack.}) 6. f3 {This is a very useful (often essential) move in such positions. Kasparov secures e4 and keeps a knight out of g4.} 6... b5 {Topalov expands on the queenside.} 7. Nge2 {This move is slightly odd since the knight has nowhere good to go right away and blocks the Bf1.} (7. Bd3 $14 {Stockfish prefers developing the bishop.}) 7... Nbd7 {The knight develops to its most natural square, controlling e5 and c5.} 8. Bh6 {A very committal decision from Kasparov. He elects to exchange the "dragon bishop," but he must sideline his queen.} 8... Bxh6 {Topalov pulls Kasparov's queen to h6, where it is misplaced.} (8... O-O $2 {This would be very risky as Kasparov can immediately launch a kingside attack.} 9. h4 $16) 9. Qxh6 {recapturing} 9... Bb7 {The bishop develops and adds important control to the d5-square.} 10. a3 {Kasparov takes a moment to stop ...b4.} (10. Qg7 {Many beginners might play this move.} 10... Rg8 {White can only retreat and nothing was accomplished.}) 10... e5 {Topalov finally makes a control commitment. He also shows his plan, ...Qe7 and 0-0-0.} (10... a5 $5 $14 {The engine preferred more queenside expansion.}) 11. O-O-O {Now that Topalov has committed, Kasparov does too.} 11... Qe7 {Topalov places the queen in a perfect spot.} 12. Kb1 $1 {A grandmaster move! Kasparov is patient and places his king on the safer b1-square.} 12... a6 {Topalov secures b5.} 13. Nc1 $1 {The knight repositions and frees the f1-bishop.} 13... O-O-O {Topalov finally castles.} 14. Nb3 {The knight finishes its journey and has a possible new target, a5.} 14... exd4 {Topalov decides it's time to release the central tensions.} 15. Rxd4 {Recapturing with the knight was of roughly equal value.} 15... c5 {The b7-bishop is released with a gain of tempo on the rook.} 16. Rd1 {The rook retreats to the first rank.} 16... Nb6 {This one move activates both the knight and the Rd8 in the fight for d5.} 17. g3 {Kasparov needs to activate his f1-bishop and h1-rook so he prepares Bh3.} 17... Kb8 {Topalov simply anticipates Bh3+.} 18. Na5 $6 {Kasparov plays to trade off the b7-bishop, but Topalov can let him have it and use the time gained to break in the center.} (18. Qf4 $16) 18... Ba8 $6 {Topalov keeps the bishop, but he did not have to do so.} (18... d5 $1 {This was the perfect time to break in the center!} 19. Nxb7 Kxb7 20. exd5 Nfxd5 $11 {Black's king feels drafty, but his central pieces offset this concern.}) 19. Bh3 $2 {Kasparov develops the bishop, but it would not be so useful on h3 had Topalov responded accurately.} (19. Qf4 $16 {again, it was better to recentralize.}) 19... d5 $1 {Topalov finally strikes out! His king is opened up, but his pieces are activated. Black is even better.} 20. Qf4+ {The queen recentralizes with a check.} 20... Ka7 {Topalov's king appears to be fairly safe on a7.} 21. Rhe1 {Kasparov finally develops his last piece.} 21... d4 {Topalov keeps the e-file from opening and asks the knight to passively retreat.} 22. Nd5 {Kasparov strives to avoid passivity. This is the move which commits Kasparov to a sacrificial path.} 22... Nbxd5 {This is the correct knight to capture with as the black king has access to b6 now.} 23. exd5 {opening the e-file.} 23... Qd6 {The queen blockades the d-pawn.} 24. Rxd4 $3 {A thunderous move! Kasparov sacrifices a rook in the hope of a mating attack.} (24. Nc6+ $5 {This might be the "best" course of action, but only Black can be better in the endgame.} 24... Bxc6 25. Qxd6 Rxd6 26. dxc6 $17) 24... cxd4 $2 {Topalov accepts. Here Topalov gets a lesson as Kasparov's sacrifice proves sound. Declining the sacrifice could have gained a clear advantage.} (24... Kb6 $1 {This move was much cited after the match. Instead of taking the rook, Black plays a daring king move. An endgame is now unavoidable.} 25. b4 Qxf4 26. Rxf4 Nxd5 27. Rxf7 cxb4 28. axb4 Nxb4 29. Nb3 Bd5 30. Rf6+ Nc6 $17 {Black is better in this endgame.}) (24... Rhe8 $2 25. Rxe8 Nxe8 26. Qxf7+ $16) 25. Re7+ $3 {A second rook sacrifice to justify the first! This one cannot be accepted.} (25. Qxd4+ $4 Qb6 26. Re7+ Nd7 {And since White's queen is hanging, the attack falters.}) 25... Kb6 {Topalov has no choice but to run the monarch up the board.} (25... Qxe7 $2 26. Qxd4+ Kb8 27. Qb6+ Bb7 28. Nc6+ Ka8 29. Qa7#) (25... Kb8 $2 26. Qxd4 Nd7 27. Rxd7 Rxd7 28. Bxd7 Qxd7 29. Qxh8+ $18) 26. Qxd4+ $1 {The knight on a5 is sacrificed as well to force Topalov's king into a mating net.} 26... Kxa5 {Topalov accepts the knight.} (26... Qc5 27. Qxf6+ Qd6 28. Be6 $3 {An amazing solution! This stops the queen trades and keeps White's pieces dominating.}) 27. b4+ {Forcing the king to a4.} 27... Ka4 {Can the king survive here?} 28. Qc3 {Kasparov threatens mate with Qb3.} (28. Ra7 $1 {This is even stronger thanks to some great resources.} 28... Bb7 29. Rxb7 $18) 28... Qxd5 (28... Bxd5 $2 29. Kb2 Qxe7 30. Qb3+ $1 Bxb3 31. cxb3# {What a stunning checkmate!}) 29. Ra7 29... Bb7 $1 {The only viable way to defend a6 is to give up this bishop.} (29... Rd6 $2 30. Kb2 Qd4 31. Qxd4 Rxd4 32. Rxa6#) 30. Rxb7 {Kasparov takes the bishop.} 30... Qc4 {Topalov offers a queen trade and resolves the threat of Qb3#.} 31. Qxf6 {Kasparov can win a knight while evading simplification.} 31... Kxa3 $2 {Topalov elects to take a pawn.} (31... Rd1+ $1 {This was the last viable defense.} 32. Kb2 Ra8 33. Qb6 Qd4+ 34. Qxd4 Rxd4 35. Rxf7 $14) 32. Qxa6+ {The play is forced from here on.} 32... Kxb4 {Topalov has eliminated the dangerous a3-b4 pawns.} 33. c3+ $1 {Kasparov shows that the attack is not over!} 33... Kxc3 {This is the most logical try.} (33... Qxc3 $2 34. Qxb5+ Ka3 35. Qa6+ Qa5 36. Qxa5#) 34. Qa1+ $1 {There is something particularly beautiful about the queen falling back to the corner.} 34... Kd2 {Perhaps the king will be safe on d1?} 35. Qb2+ {Kasparov continues the hunt.} 35... Kd1 {Topalov's king reaches the opposite rank, and it looks safe on d1!} 36. Bf1 $3 {AMAZING! Kasparov delivers a shot that wins the game. The bishop cannot be taken.} 36... Rd2 {A great try from Topalov! He leaves his queen hanging and counter-attacks.} (36... Qxf1 37. Qc2+ Ke1 38. Re7+ $18) 37. Rd7 $3 {Kasparov has all the answers. He pins the d2-rook.} 37... Rxd7 {Topalov has no choice. He must surrender his queen.} 38. Bxc4 {cashing in.} 38... bxc4 {recapturing.} 39. Qxh8 {The "sting in the tail" of this long battle.} 39... Rd3 {Threatening the f3-pawn.} 40. Qa8 {Defending f3 and threatening Qa4+.} 40... c3 {Threatening a winning c2+.} 41. Qa4+ {Resolving the c2 threat.} 41... Ke1 {hoping to attack the kingside pawns.} 42. Qe4 {Topalov resigned here.} 1-0
